<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-106-004  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 106 004.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  Feb 1990 v7 n2 p241(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting started with utilities. (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Heid, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Utility programs enhance the Macintosh's capabilities and allowuses to customize their systems.andP;  There are two basic categoriesof utilities: those that work with an application, deskaccessories or INITs (start-up documents), and utilities that areseparate applications for performing specific tasks such astransferring files between computers or performing backuproutines.andP;  Numerous types of utility programs are discussedincluding navigation utilities, resource-management utilities,text-retrieval utilities, partitioning utilities, defragmentationutilities (or disk optimizers), backup utilities and fileutilities.andP;  Brief descriptions are additionally provided forcosmetic utilities, screen savers, screen capture utilities,workgroup utilities, spoolers, file-transfer utilities,file-compression utilities and INIT managers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     TutorialUtility ProgramsEnhancementsDesktop Organizers.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   What specific utility toolboxes do best. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>